hn</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Iefan","meanings":["Later form of   Ieuan ."]},{"name":"Ifan","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."]},{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]},{"name":"\"Bach\"","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Zachary  , also used as an independent given name."],"variants":[{"name":"Zachary","meanings":["vernacular form of the New Testament Greek name <i>Zacharias</i>, a form of Hebrew   Zechariah   ‘God has remembered’. This was the name of the father of John the Baptist, who underwent a temporary period of dumbness for his lack of faith (Luke 1), and of a more obscure figure, Zacharias son of Barachias, who was slain ‘between the temple and the altar’ (Matthew 23:35; Luke 11:51). In the United States it is familiar as the name of a 19th-century president,  Zachary Taylor . Since the 1990s the name has been remarkably popular in the English-speaking world, especially in the United States."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ieuan \"Bach\" ap Dafydd was born in 1465, in Glamorgan, Wales, his father, Syr Dafydd ap Jenkin Jenkin of Llan-arth, was 26 and his mother, Gwenllian ferch Lewys, was 21. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Catrin ferch Dafydd \"Anwyl\"."},"et":{"1465–":"1465–Surnud","1465–Male":"1465–Surnud","1472–Male":"1472–Surnud","1474–1542":"1474–1542","1476–Male":"1476–Surnud","1478–Male":"1478–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1501–Female":"1501–Surnud","1520–1576":"1520–1576","1440–Male":"1440–Surnud","1445–Female":"1445–Surnud","1501":"1501","1445":"1445","1478":"1478","1576":"1576","1465":"1465","1520":"1520","1476":"1476","1542":"1542","1474":"1474","1440":"1440","1472":"1472","of,,Glamorganshire,Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales","Llanfeugan, Breconshire, W